ory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F017294/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>In spite of the well known potential benefits for aggregate welfare, the labour market effects of increased globalisation have become a major source of anxiety in recent years. Within this debate, the spectre that closer integration induces trade unions to engage in a race-to-the-bottom in wages appears to be a particular cause of concern. This research project investigates, both from a theoretical and empirical perspective, the effects of increased globalisation on collective bargaining outcomes. The theoretical analysis develops models in which imperfect product market competition generates rents which unions seek to capture in the form of higher wages. The analysis focuses on some unsolved issues in the literature, which have significant policy implications. For example, how does trade liberalisation impact on bargained wages and union density if unions are open shops and membership is not compulsory? How does firm entry and falling trade costs influence the interactions between unionised and nonunionised sectors in general equilibrium? How do these effects depend on the equilibrium trade regime? The theoretical predictions are then examined econometrically, using a particularly comprehensive administrative dataset for Portugal which matches information on virtually all workers, firms and collective bargaining agreements over the 1986-2004 period.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>10291</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutp